{
  "text": "Tracking There has been a lot of research in the area of object tracking. In this section we will focus on CNN based solutions [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . They all take the approach of tracking-by-detection, where a binary classifier is applied to positive and negative samples from each frame. Typically, the object bounding box of just the first frame is provided and the CNN models learnt in an online manner. All methods need to somehow deal with the small number of labeled training samples. [CITATION_8] pretrains the network using an autoencoder, [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] uses CNNs pretrained on the large ImageNet dataset and [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] uses special loss functions and sampling techniques to cope with the small number of training samples. In contrast to most existing work, our solution first finds location candidates for each frame and then applies global constraints to create the motion trajectory, which is used to provide smoothly tracked output that aids the next stage of the system.",
  "correct_citation": {
